04464nam a22006015i 9780774855143DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072006xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748551437 a10.59962/97807748551432doi  a(DE-B1597)661925  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHQ76.27.Y68.F54 2006eb 7aSOC0120002bisacsh04a306.761 aFilax, Gloria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQueer Youth in the Province of the "Severely Normal" /cGloria Filax. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (200 p.) :b11 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSexuality Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tGendering: Troubled Theories, Troubling Identities -- tProduction and Consumption of Youth Identity -- tSocial/Legal Production of Sexual Minorities in Canada -- tQueer Identities and Strange Representations in the Province of the Severely Normal -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe government of Alberta in the 1990s actively contested the legal rights of sexual minority citizens. Provincial premier Ralph Klein defended this position by claiming that most Albertans, whom he characterized as "severely normal," were not in favour of recognizing homosexuality as a protected category in the provincial human rights code. Gloria Filax explores how youth identities have been constructed through dominant and often competing discourses about youth, sexuality, and gender, and how queer youth in the province of Alberta negotiated the contradictions of these discourses. She juxtaposes the voices of queer young people in Alberta with discourses that claim expert knowledge about young people's lives. She also explores what queer youth have to say about their lives in relation to renditions of homosexuality from the Alberta Report, a weekly magazine published in the 1990s that, despite its fiscal marginality, had significant impact on social values in Alberta. This book is important because it presents the voices of queer youth, particularly in the context of expert and popular discourses that often overwhelmingly deny the value of their lives. A significant contribution to queer social science scholarship, Queer Youth in the Province of the "Severely Normal" will also be of interest to sociologists, educators, social workers, and counsellors.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGay youthxGovernment policyzAlbertaxHistoryy20th century. 0aGay youthxGovernment policyzAlbertay20th century. 0aGay youthzAlbertaxHistoryy20th century. 0aHomophobiaxPress coveragezAlbertaxHistoryy20th century. 0aHomophobiazAlbertaxHistoryy20th century. 0aHomophobiazAlbertay20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485514340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774855143423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774855143/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles